{{Infobox organization |name = 56 Group Wales |image = |image_border = |size = 200px |alt = |abbreviation = |motto = |formation = 1956 |type = Visual arts |location = Wales |membership = {{Plainlist| Ken Elias * Dennis Gardiner * Robert Harding * Sue Hiley Harris * Carol Hiles * Harvey Hood * Robert Alwyn Hughes * Sue Hunt * Dilys Jackson * Justine Johnson * Glyn Jones * Martyn Jones * Kay Keogh * Alison Lochhead * Tiff Oben * Tom Piper * Richard Renshaw * Corinthe Rizvi * Pete Seabourne * John Selway * Kevin Sinnott * Antonia Spowers * Peter Spriggs * Pete Williams
}} | website = {{url|www.56groupwales.org.uk}} }}
The '''56 Group Wales''' ({{lang-cy|'''Grŵp 56 Cymru'''}}) is an artists' organisation founded in [[Wales]] in 1956, with the aim of promoting Welsh [[Modernist]] art and artists.<ref name="50 years">Peter Wakelin, [https://books.google.com/books?id=aXYySHER7x8C&pg=PA43&dq=Arthur+Giardelli&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xFpTT5i_EKOA0AXpzLDpCw&ved=0CF8QuwUwCA#v=onepage&q=Arthur%20Giardelli&f=false "50 years of the Welsh Group"], National Museum of Wales (1999), {{ISBN|0-7200-0472-1}}</ref> The name was originally simply the '''56 Group''': "Wales" was added in 1967, in response to a feeling that the organisation's "Welsh origins ought to be re-affirmed".<ref>Moore 2012, p. 21.</ref> The [[Welsh language|Welsh-language]] version of the name was first used on publicity in 1976.<ref>Moore 2012, p. 44.</ref>
==Formation== The post-war art establishment in Wales was still very conservative and moves had been afoot since the late 1930s to create a modern art group.<ref name="50 years 14">Peter Wakelin, [https://books.google.com/books?id=aXYySHER7x8C&pg=PA43&dq=Arthur+Giardelli&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xFpTT5i_EKOA0AXpzLDpCw&ved=0CF8QuwUwCA#v=onepage&q=Arthur%20Giardelli&f=false "50 years of the Welsh Group"], National Museum of Wales (1999), pp. 14-15, {{ISBN|0-7200-0472-1}}</ref> In March 1956, following a failed attempt to become a ''South Wales Academy of Art'', a "rebellion" took place within the ranks of the ''[[The Welsh Group|South Wales Group]]'' and the ''56 Group'' was established.<ref name="50 years 39">Peter Wakelin, [https://books.google.com/books?id=aXYySHER7x8C&pg=PA43&dq=Arthur+Giardelli&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xFpTT5i_EKOA0AXpzLDpCw&ved=0CF8QuwUwCA#v=onepage&q=Arthur%20Giardelli&f=false "50 years of the Welsh Group"], National Museum of Wales (1999), pp. 39-43, {{ISBN|0-7200-0472-1}}</ref> Artists [[Eric Malthouse]], [[David Tinker (artist)|David Tinker]] and [[Michael Edmonds (artist)|Michael Edmonds]] were the leading instigators. They circulated a statement of purpose and aims and an invitation to join the group to ten leading Welsh artists.
{{cquote|That painters and sculptors believe in a positive and dynamic approach which is aware of the tradition of the past and its fulfilment in the Art of the present.
That the first aims of painting and sculpture lie in the integration of design and emotion; the search for a powerful image that transcends the everyday world around us.
That the effect of environment is deeper and more all-embracing than the fortuitous mimicry of everyday surroundings. The painter and sculptor consciously seek a place to work where he feels at home. |author=Eric Malthouse, David Tinker and Michael Edmonds |source=''The 56 Group'': statement of purpose, 1956<ref>Moore 2012, p. 7.</ref>}}
Of those invited to join, nine accepted: Trevor Bates, [[Hubert Dalwood]], George Fairley, [[Arthur Giardelli]], Robert Hunter, [[Heinz Koppel]], [[Will Roberts]], John Wright and [[Ernest Zobole]].<ref name="Art in Wales">Eric Rowan, "Art in Wales: An Illustrated History 1850 - 1980", University of Wales Press, Cardiff (1985), pp. 125-129. {{ISBN|0-7083-1408-2}}</ref><ref>Moore 2012, p. 7.</ref> [[Brenda Chamberlain (artist)|Brenda Chamberlain]], the only female artist invited, declined.<ref>Moore 2012, pp. 7, 32.</ref>
Although all twelve of the founder-members worked in a broadly modernist and internationalist idiom, they did not share a recognisably common style or ideology. Their average age was 36; and ten worked as [[Art education|art lecturers]] (Roberts and Edmonds did not). Only two, Roberts and Zobole, had been born in Wales: Fairley was born in [[Scotland]], Koppel in [[Germany]] and the others in [[England]].<ref>Moore 2012, p. 7.</ref>
==Activities== The 56 Group has always been essentially an exhibiting association of artists who retain their own independence and individuality. The group's first exhibition was held at [[Worcester]] Museum and Art Gallery in June 1957, and versions of the same exhibition were held later the same year at the [[National Museum Cardiff|National Museum of Wales]] and [[Tenby]] Civic Centre.<ref>Moore 2012, pp. 14–15.</ref> It subsequently exhibited widely in both Wales and England. Its first continental exhibition was held in [[Amsterdam]] in 1967, and later exhibitions went to [[Nantes]] in 1974–5, [[Bologna]] in 1983, [[Czechoslovakia]] in 1986–7 and again in 1991, and [[Libramont-Chevigny|Libramont]], Belgium, in 1994.<ref>Moore 2012, pp. 22, 38, 58–9, 64–5, 69, 72.</ref> An exhibition of modern Welsh art held at the [[Jefferson Place Gallery]], [[Washington, D.C.]] in 1965, although not formally associated with the Group, included work by several of its members.<ref name="Art in Wales" /><ref>Moore 2012, p. 20.</ref> By 2012, the Group's 56th anniversary year, it could claim to have had a total of 88 full members (plus a number of guest, associate and honorary members);<ref>Full listings of the membership appear in Moore 2012, pp. 88–91.</ref> and to have held 225 exhibition showings.<ref>Moore 2012, p. 86. A full listing of exhibitions appears in Moore 2012, pp. 92–4.</ref>
Painter, sculptor and teacher [[Arthur Giardelli]] was the chair of the Group from 1961 to 1998. Some of its success – exhibitions and tours outside Wales – have been attributed to his language skills and European outlook.<ref name="Giardelli Guardian">David Moore, [https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2009/nov/11/arthur-giardelli-obituary Arthur Giardelli obituary], ''The Guardian'' (London), 11 November 2009. Retrieved 2012-03-06.</ref><ref>Moore 2012, pp. 11, 52.</ref>
In 2012, marking the 56th anniversary of the group's formation, a touring exhibition visited galleries around Wales. Called ''The 56 Group Wales: The Founders'', it includes artworks of the twelve original founders, as well as work from current members.<ref name="WM three new shows">Nathan Bevan, [http://www.walesonline.co.uk/showbiz-and-lifestyle/arts-in-wales/2012/04/02/radical-post-war-arts-collective-the-56-group-returns-in-three-new-shows-91466-30671922/2/ 'Radical post-war arts collective the 56 Group returns in three new shows'], Western Mail, 2 April 2012. Retrieved 2012-07-22.</ref> For the previous ten years, businessman Barrie Maskell had spent time tracking down and purchasing work made by each of the twelve original members. This included a visit to one of the surviving founders, John Wright, who was living in Spain.<ref name="WM three new shows" /> Fifty-six of Maskell's paintings were chosen for the exhibition. The exhibition was shown at venues in Pontypridd, Cardiff and [[MOMA, Wales|MOMA Wales]] in [[Machynlleth]].<ref name="WM three new shows" /> In the same year, a history of the Group's first 56 years by David Moore was published.<ref>Moore 2012.</ref>
In January 2013 a touring exhibition of the group's work, ''56:56'', opened at Newport Art Gallery.<ref>[http://content.yudu.com/Library/A20nlz/SouthWalesArgusGuide/resources/7.htm 'Art tour celebrates 56 years'], ''South Wales Argus'', 11 January 2013. Retrieved 9 March 2013.</ref>
==Criticism== The Group's activities have not always been eulogised. [[Will Roberts]], one of the founder members, who was afterwards (in 1964) asked to withdraw from exhibitions because his work was seen as insufficiently radical, later dismissed the Group as having been "set up by art school teachers who wanted to sell their work".<ref>Moore 2012, p. 12.</ref> When Rollo Charles, keeper of art at the National Museum of Wales, commented in 1976 that the Group "is now generally regarded as the official avant garde of Welsh art", critic Bryn Richards responded "[t]his must seem to those who founded the group, with such hope, as a veritable kiss of death".<ref>Moore 2012, p. 45.</ref> Renowned Welsh artist [[Kyffin Williams]] was reported in 1981 to have had a strong antipathy for what he described as a group of "predominantly abstract painters or English [[carpetbagger]]s, ... who came down to Wales because they could not make it in the metropolis. The 56 Group has taken over Welsh art, and he [Williams] is out of favour in his homeland as a result."<ref>Moore 2012, p. 54: quoting "Painting: Kyffin Williams", ''Avant Garde'', Spring/Summer 1981.</ref>
