'''''Savušun''''' (also spelled '''''Savushun,''''' {{lang-fa|سووشون}}) is a 1969 [[Persian language|Persian]] [[novel]] by Iranian female writer [[Simin Daneshvar]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://www.michiganquarterlyreview.com/2017/02/modern-iran-through-its-novels/|title=Modern Iran Through Its Novels|date=2017-02-23|work=Michigan Quarterly Review|access-date=2018-01-21|language=en-US}}</ref> It is the first novel in Persian written by a female author.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/suvashun|title=SUVASHUN|last=Masʿud Jaʿfari Jazi|first=|date=April 12, 2012|website=Encyclopaedia Iranica|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-01-21}}</ref> The story is about the life of a landowning family in [[Shiraz]] faced to the occupation of [[Iran]] during [[World War II]].<ref name=":0" /> ''Savušun'' has sold over five hundred thousand copies in Iran.<ref name=":0" />

''Savušun'' is "groundbreaking" and highly acclaimed work in contemporary [[Persian language|Persian]] literature, with both literary and popular success within and outside Iran.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=http://www.yourmiddleeast.com/features/savushun-a-novel-about-modern-iran_9350|title=Savushun: A novel about modern Iran|last=|first=|date=|work=Your Middle East|access-date=2018-01-21|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> The novel has been translated to [[English language|English]] and 16 other languages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/persian/mobile/arts/2012/03/120308_l41_simin_daneshvar_obituary.shtml|title=BBC فارسی - فرهنگ و هنر - سیمین دانشور، داستان نویس و مترجم برجسته ایرانی، درگذشت|website=www.bbc.co.uk|language=fa|access-date=2018-01-21}}</ref> When writing about the novel's importance, critic [[Kaveh Bissari]] describing an exact translation by [[Ghanoonparvar]] in 1990 and the version ''A Persian Requiem'' by Roxane Zand in 1991.<ref name=":0" />

Daneshvar uses [[folklore]] and [[myth]] in ''Savušun.'' Linguistically, ''savušun'' is a corruption of ''[[Siyâvašun]]'', which refers to the traditional mourning for [[Siyâvaš]], a hero in the ''[[Šâhnâme]]''.<ref name=":1" />

