The '''Symphony No. 1''' is the first [[symphony]] by the American composer [[John Harbison]]. The work was commissioned by the [[Boston Symphony Orchestra]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Powers |first=Keith |title=Morlot takes up the BSO's Harbison mantle in convincing fashion |work=Boston Classical Review |date=November 25, 2011 |url=http://bostonclassicalreview.com/2011/11/morlot-takes-up-the-bsos-harbison-mantle-in-convincing-fashion/ |accessdate=April 30, 2016}}</ref> and was composed in 1981. It was given its world premiere in [[Boston]] on March 22, 1984 by the Boston Symphony Orchestra under the conductor [[Seiji Ozawa]].<ref name="Score">{{cite web |last=Harbison |first=John |authorlink=John Harbison |year=1981 |title=Symphony No. 1 |publisher=[[G. Schirmer Inc.]] |url=http://www.musicsalesclassical.com/composer/work/627/37276 |accessdate=April 30, 2016}}</ref> {{external media | width = 210px | float = right | video1 = [http://bostonlocaltv.org/catalog/V_16JCX2N2320DW8T John Harbison (on his Symphony No. 1)], March 22, 1984, 4:20, [[WGBH Educational Foundation|Boston TV Digital Archive]]<ref name="wgbh">[http://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip_15-br8mc8rk4z “Ten O'Clock News; John Harbison,”] 1984-03-22, 4:20, [[WGBH Educational Foundation|WGBH]], [[American Archive of Public Broadcasting]] (WGBH and the [[Library of Congress]]), Boston, MA and Washington, DC, accessed September 23, 2016.</ref> }}
==Composition== The symphony has a duration of roughly 24 minutes and is composed in four [[Movement (music)|movements]]: #Drammatico #Allegro sfumato #Paesaggio: andante #Tempo giusto
===Instrumentation=== The work is scored for a large orchestra comprising three [[Western concert flute|flutes]] (doubling [[piccolo]] and [[alto flute]]), three [[oboe]]s (doubling [[Cor anglais|English horn]]), three [[clarinet]]s (doubling [[bass clarinet]]), three [[bassoon]]s (doubling [[contrabassoon]]), four [[French horn|horns]], two [[trumpet]]s, three [[trombone]]s, [[tuba]], [[timpani]], six percussionists, [[Pedal harp|harp]], and [[String section|strings]].<ref name="Score" />
==Reception== Reviewing a 1989 performance by the [[Philadelphia Orchestra]], Lesley Valdes of ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' wrote, "Although it sometimes overstresses its points, the symphony has heft and atmosphere." She added:{{quote|The symphony does not lack for musical ideas, which appear to be organized tidily; some are presented with fine imagination. Atmosphere, more than dramatic import, appears the composer's suit; and for ideas and atmospheric effect, one most admired the work's inner movements. The second, a sort of scherzo, features the woodwinds in lissome questionings that are summarily answered by the horns. The andante offers the sort of shimmery-to-sustained string playing that calls to mind foggy landscapes a la Eugene O'Neill; its melancholy state was excellently indicated by conductor and ensemble alike.<ref>{{cite web |last=Valdes |first=Lesley |title=Comet Leads Philadelphia Orchestra |work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |date=October 6, 1989 |url=http://articles.philly.com/1989-10-06/entertainment/26116915_1_catherine-comet-philadelphia-orchestra-high-notes |accessdate=April 30, 2016}}</ref>}}
